\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Modelling responsiveness and willingness to negotiate using sentiment: textual
 analysis of the FARC-Colombia peace talks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Leslie Huang
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
New York University Department of Politics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
M.A.
 paper
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Adviser: Arthur Spirling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
This paper considers factors during the peace process that may explain the
 success or failure of peace negotiations and ultimately peace agreements.
 The FARC-Colombia peace talks from 2012-2016, although marred by continued
 fighting, sought to end an intractable half-century-long conflict with
 a negotiated settlement.
 Using a new dataset of statements from the Colombian government, FARC (Fuerzas
 Armadas Revolucionarias de Colombia), and the joint peace negotiators,
 I employ sentiment analysis and hidden Markov models to estimate each actor's
 willingness to negotiate as a function of their textual sentiment.
 I find that estimates of FARC and government willingness to negotiate can
 predict the sentiment of jointly released statements.
 I also use a Markov process to estimate sentiment responsiveness.
 I show that actors are more likely to respond to each other's statements
 with the same level of sentiment.
 These results suggest that this method of measuring the progress of peace
 talks is a promising new tool for research on why talks are successful
 or derailed by violence and, ultimately, why peace is durable after certain
 conflicts but not others.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why do some peace negotiations succeed while others fall apart, and what
 accounts for the durability of peace after some conflicts but not others?
 Better understanding the puzzles behind successful conflict termination
 is of great academic and real-world importance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Analysis of peace processes, such as in the Middle East, has tended to be
 historical and case-specific or game theoretical 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "barak2005failure"

\end_inset

.
 Researchers have offered theories to explain the variable effect of violent
 attacks on derailing peace talks 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kydd-walter"

\end_inset

 and the relationship between government concessions and the level of terrorist
 activity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "demesquita-conciliation"

\end_inset

.
 Often these accounts are driven by or complicated by an information asymmetry
 about whether actors are sincere and by the disconnect between unitary
 negotiants (government, rebel) and the cacophony of factions that each
 contains, as internal contestation and excluded or disgruntled parties
 can spoil the peace process 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "stedman1997spoiler,pearlman2009spoiling"

\end_inset

, although more recent research has found that including all rebel groups/factio
ns is less important than originally thought 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "nilsson2008partial"

\end_inset

.
 Other theoretical explanations of peace process failure as a commitment
 problem point toward the implementation of agreements as the reason for
 failure 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "walter2002committing"

\end_inset

.
 Accordingly, postconflict research has examined the significance of effect
 of peacekeeping operations and other third-party guarantees 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "fortna2004does,fortna2008does"

\end_inset

.
 Other research on postconflict transitions has examined the texts of peace
 agreements to better understand whether provisions such as political representa
tion for rebels in postconflict governments predict peace survival 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hartzell2001stabilizing"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Understanding the peace process is a key to understanding how agreements
 are produced and why some of them are successful.
 Researchers have examined many features of the negotiations process, but
 to my knowledge there is no research that analyzes texts issued from peace
 negotiations other than the final agreement itself, nor has sentiment analysis
 previously been used to study peace processes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To fill this gap, this paper makes several original contributions.
 First, I collect a new dataset of texts from the Colombian government and
 FARC, in addition to joint statements issued by the peace negotiators,
 from an ongoing conflict/negotiation period (2012-2016).
 Using text analysis methods from psychology and natural language processing
 to measure the sentiment of documents, I use hidden Markov models to estimate
 the state of the peace talks in terms of each actor's willingness to negotiate.
 I also use sentiment analysis and Markov processes to model whether the
 sentiment of one actor's statement can predict the sentiment of a subsequent
 statement from another actor--e.g.
 whether FARC is more likely to respond to a positive government statement
 with a positive statement of its own rather than a negative one.
 These methods enable researchers to measure the progress of peace talks,
 whether our interest is in how the state of the peace process affects the
 level of violence, agreement provisions, or durability of peace.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although it is difficult to draw causal conclusions from observational data,
 texts from peace negotiations are a promising and heretofore unutilized
 source of information about the state of the peace process.
 A better understanding of these processes has valuable real-world implications:
 measuring the persistence of negative sentiment in fragile negotiations,
 for example, may help us explain the mechanisms through which extremist
 attacks derail peace talks.
 Moreover, understanding how sentiment responds to sentiment may yield insights
 about signalling and bluffing not only in peace negotiations but also in
 the exchanges between countries that avoid or lead down the path to war.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Background and literature
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
FARC (Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia) was founded in 1964, in the
 aftermath of the ten-year period of civil war known as La Violencia.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The group's rarely used, official name is Fuerzas Armadas Revolucionarias
 de Colombia--Ejército del Pueblo (People's Army), or FARC-EP.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Originally a Marxist insurgency seeking to overthrow the government, FARC's
 supporters were mainly communists and rural peasants
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "CFR"

\end_inset

.
 FARC's current circumstances can be traced to the 1980s and 1990s, when
 it began to tax cocaine producers, soon becoming involved in cocaine production
 itself
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "wilson-center"

\end_inset

.
 This sparked the formation of right-wing paramilitary groups, such as the
 Autodefensas Unidas de Colombia (AUC; United Self-Defense Forces of Colombia),
 who battled FARC about, inter alia, control over drug trafficking
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "wilson-center"

\end_inset

.
 FARC's tactics have included murder, kidnappings for ransom, disappearances
 of civilians and security personnel, and extortion; less widely known abroad
 is their use of landmines, which killed or maimed thousands, and their
 kidnapping and forced conscription of child soldiers.
 The right-wing paramilitaries used many of the same tactics as well; AUC
 was also labelled a terrorist organization and was also involved in drug
 trafficking prior to being disbanded in the mid-2000s
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "colombiareports-auc"

\end_inset

.
 FARC, the paramilitary groups, and the government have all been accused
 of human rights abuses in the violence, which has claimed the lives of
 more than 200,000 civilians and displaced millions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "bbc-ceasefire"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The Ejército de Liberación Nacional (ELN; National Liberation Army), a smaller
 and also Marxist group, has much the same history as FARC: it was founded
 around the same time and has also engaged in murder, kidnappings, extortion,
 and other violence
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CFR"

\end_inset

.
 ELN began pursuing cooperation with FARC and peace talks with the government
 as FARC's peace process came underway over the last several years.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 During the '80s, FARC also co-founded a political party, the Patriotic
 Union, which had declined into nonexistence by the '90s after thousands
 of its members, politicians, and candidates were murdered
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "nyt-UP"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
During the tenure of president (now senator) Álvaro Uribe from 2002-2010,
 the government cracked down on Marxist groups and drug traffickers, significant
ly reducing the strength of FARC.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CFR"

\end_inset

 FARC's willingness to negotiate, after more than fifty years of the longest-run
ning insurgency in the Western Hemisphere, is generally attributed in part
 to this crackdown.
 Peace talks, brokered by Cuba and Norway, commenced in the fall of 2012
 in Havana and have been championed by president Juan Manuel Santos.
 The talks were limited to an agenda of six topics: agrarian reform/land
 development; political participation; ending of the conflict (i.e.
 ceasefire, post-conflict justice, disarmament, and reintegration); illegal
 drugs; victims; and implementation.
 Over the course of the peace process, negotiators came to preliminary agreement
s for these topics, which will be included in the final peace deal.
 Despite this, Santos's approval ratings have plummeted since he took office,
 because of public skepticism/pessimism about the talks and the vociferous
 opposition of right-wing politicians such as Uribe, as well as some members
 of the military, that oppose agreement provisions which, in their view,
 give the former rebels political representation and amnesty instead of
 prosecution for crimes committed
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "nyt,isaacson"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With many of its leaders and founders killed in the years leading up to
 the negotiations, FARC is currently led by a rebel known as Timochenko.
 Their negotiating team, led by the rebel alias Ivan Marquez, is comprised
 of numerous Secretariat members and has included top members from key Fronts
 (regional subdivisions).
 Despite this high-ranking participation and FARC's declaration of several
 unilateral ceasefires during the negotiations period, attacks have continued
 during the peace talks, ranging from the killings of rural policemen to
 the kidnapping of a high-ranking general and the bombing of oil pipelines.
 Throughout (and prior to) the talks, FARC has released public statements
 on their website and have created an additional website about the peace
 process, which features the individual blogs of negotiators.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See, for instance, http://pazfarc-ep.org/index.php/ivan-marquez
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This project examines texts from the peace process up until May 31, 2016;
 however, it should be noted that president Santos and Timochenko signed
 a bilateral ceasefire agreement on June 22, 2016, and announced that they
 had reached a final deal on August 24, 2016, which will subsequently face
 a popular referendum
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "guardian-agreement"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Sentiment analysis of extremist texts 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Text analysis of extremist texts (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

text
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 being any form of written or transcribed statement) originated with Pennebaker
 and coauthors in the field of psychology
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "tausczik-pennebaker"

\end_inset

.
 Focusing on divining the emotional and psychological states of individuals,
 this research has found associations between frequency of usage of particular
 types of words and emotional, cognitive, and social attributes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "pennebaker-chung"

\end_inset

.
 In analysis of extremist texts from American Nazi and militant animal rights
 organizations, for instance, Pennebaker and Chung found that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

third-person plural pronouns are the single best predictor of extremism...
 suggest[ing] that the group is defining itself to a large degree by the
 existence of an oppositional group
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "pennebaker-chung"

\end_inset

.
 Consistent with that result, their study of texts issued by Osama bin Laden
 and Ayman al-Zawahiri of al Qaeda found greater frequency of third-person
 plural pronouns, as well as emotional words and first-person pronouns 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "pennebaker-chung"

\end_inset

.
 The data in that study differs in several significant ways from the data
 in this paper: those texts were translated, were authored by specific individua
ls,
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Some of the FARC statements are signed by specific individuals, but in this
 paper the author is simply 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

FARC.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 There is significant heterogeneity in the nature of government statements,
 some of which are transcripts of speeches delivered by president Santos,
 but the author is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

government
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

; and indeed, the question of whether presidents themselves have actually
 authored texts has been explored in the literature 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "sigelman"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and were originally oral rather than printed texts; nevertheless, Pennebaker
 et al.'s results are the starting point on which I base the measures of
 sentiment used in this paper.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Other analyses of extremist texts have tended to utilize large corpora of
 online postings, with a focus on the emotional affect of posts on extremist
 Internet forums 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "abbasichen"

\end_inset

, network analysis of the authors of extremist blogs 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "chau-xu"

\end_inset

, and content analysis of extremist documents 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "smith"

\end_inset

.
 Text analysis of heads of state, on the other hand, tends to have a different
 focus and can be either empirical or qualitative: George W.
 Bush's speeches following September 11, 2001, have been especially popular
 with researchers, as are propaganda devices and fear-mongering rhetoric
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "graham2004call,schonhardt2005measuring,bligh2004charisma,de-castella"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Theory and hypotheses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why does it matter how peace talks are going? First, I will discuss the
 answer to this question from a behavioral and bargaining point of view.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Impressions or assessments of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

how the talks are going
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 affect the views of the public, and decisions made by negotiants may be
 colored by answers to or beliefs about questions such as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

how serious is the other party about peace?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

how hard are they pushing for their demands?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 This paper offers new methods of measurement that get past the vagueness
 or relativism in the way these questions are stated.
 The answer to the first question, whether the other party is serious about
 negotiations, is significant for two reasons.
 To use FARC-Colombia as our example: The government wants to know, given
 the political cost of continuing to negotiate and the still heavier cost
 of a failure (during the long slog of peace talks a common observation
 was that Santos 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

has staked his legacy on the deal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "washpost-santos"

\end_inset

), whether an avowedly Marxist-Leninist group that has continued to launch
 attacks will actually follow through on a peace deal that will require
 disarmament/demobilization but almost certainly will not the implement
 of a Marxist economic-political system.
 Second, regardless of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

truth
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 about FARC's seriousness or what their demands are at the negotiating table,
 popular impressions (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

FARC is stalling
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the government isn't driving a hard enough bargain
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) affect the government's bargaining behavior and demands in public and
 in private, its level of military operations, and certainly its rhetoric.
 The government has to answer to public opinion, political opponents and,
 eventually, the next cycle of elections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More generally, peace talks are often characterized by mistrust and an inability
 to know whether the other party's statements are sincere.
 For instance, Santos's government long refused to stop military operations
 against FARC, although FARC frequently used its unilateral ceasefires to
 call for a bilateral ceasefire.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Interestingly, research by Bueno de Mesquita theorizes that violence increases
 after government concessions because more extreme members are left in control
 of their organization after moderate members accept the concessions in
 exchange for counterterrorism assistance 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "demesquita-conciliation"

\end_inset

.
 The government held out on the bilateral ceasefire, arguably FARC's most
 coveted concession, until just weeks before the final deal was reached,
 but in any event FARC has displayed a unified central command rather than
 one vulnerable to fragmentation.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The government's decision is seen as a safeguard thwarting a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

long con
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 being played by FARC--that is to say, continued military operations would
 prevent FARC from using the negotiations to stall as they increase their
 military strength 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "battaglino-lodola"

\end_inset

.
 A variety of concerns likely contributed to the government's suspicions:
 first, the criticism of politicians such as Uribe; second, continuing FARC
 attacks; and third, the fact that negotiations could very well fall apart
 without producing an agreement for other reasons.
 Although this paper focuses only on the negotiation process leading up
 to a peace agreement, mistrust can extend to the implementation of a deal
 (e.g.
 FARC would be wary of disarming or giving up secret information such as
 its members' locations if it thought the government would renege).
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
E.g.
 changes in relative military strength may cause either side to change its
 mind about deciding the outcome of the conflict at the negotiating table
 rather than on the battlefield.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Negotiations and violence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the above discussion suggests, current assessments of an actor's 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

seriousness about peace
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 factor in the level and nature of ongoing violence.
 However, to date the analysis of peace negotiations has not utilized sentiment
 analysis.
 Instead, perhaps because 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

actions speak louder than words,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the focus of much empirical research is on violence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For instance, Kydd and Walter offer a game theoretical explanation for why
 extremist violence during peace negotiations can sometimes derail talks
 by revealing information about the rebel group's capacity or willingness
 to control extremist factions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kydd-walter"

\end_inset

.
 The government cannot discern whether the rebels are sincere, bluffing
 (potentially interested in an agreement but overstating their demands to
 get a better deal), or uninterested in peace and stalling (to allow their
 forces to regroup), based on their words alone.
 Similar reasoning underlies one rationalist explanation for war, which
 is based on on the incentives of both parties to misrepresent their resolve
 to go to war and their military power 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "fearon"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But the fact is that many negotiations take place without a bilateral ceasefire,
 as the FARC negotiations did.
 Although the talks were not derailed by either regular low-intensity violence
 or shocks, they were temporarily suspended on certain occasions.
 This suggests that we may want to examine the state of the negotiations
 over than time to understand how the effects of violence unfolded differently.
 I argue that the texts issued from negotiations can be used to model the
 state of the negotiations in terms of actors' willingness to negotiate.
 With better measurement and better understanding of the dynamics of how
 agreements are reached, we may be able to learn not only about how violence
 affects talks but also how talks affect violence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another body of post-conflict research attempts to explain why war recurs
 or peace survives in different situations.
 One theoretical explanation is that most civil wars do not end with negotiated
 settlements because of bargaining failures and commitment problems: it's
 hard for people who have been killing each other to agree to stop 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "walter1997critical"

\end_inset

.
 Thus, such research argues, the key to peace survival is designing 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

credible guarantees
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to convince combatants to commit to treaties 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "walter2002committing"

\end_inset

.
 Other research on peace agreements has found that peace survival can be
 predicted by the circumstances of the just-ended conflict (e.g.
 its intensity and the nature of the previous regime), as well as provisions
 such as territorial autonomy and assurances of security made by third-party
 states or organizations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hartzell2001stabilizing"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, such research analyzes peace agreements while overlooking the dynamic
 nature of negotiations and the other texts produced in the process.
 Much as we might look at the draft bills and amendments that precede a
 piece of final legislation, if we want to understand what contributes to
 durable peace, or why bargaining falls apart, we should be interested not
 only in the end result, but also in the process that generates agreements
 or fails to achieve them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Hypotheses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper cannot answer all of the questions posed in the section above,
 but it does introduce new measurement techniques that can aid in those
 answers.
 I present a regime-switching Markov model that estimates an actor's willingness
 to negotiate using measures of negative and positive emotion.
 To validate the states that the model predicts, I predict there is a positive
 relationship between a predicted state of high willingness to negotiate
 and the sentiment and incidence of joint statements.
 When FARC and/or the government are predicted to be in a conciliatory rather
 than a hardline state, joint statements should be more likely to occur
 and their sentiment should be more positive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the second part of the paper, I model the responsiveness of sentiment
 using another Markov process.
 I hypothesize that an actor is more likely to respond with the same level
 of sentiment used by the other actor in the most recent statement.
 In other words, if FARC issues a statement with high (positive) sentiment,
 the following government statement is more likely to respond with high
 rather than low (negative) sentiment, and vice versa.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper uses an original dataset of (1) communiqués issued by FARC, (2)
 statements of the Colombian government, and (3) joint communiqués issued
 by the peace negotiators.
 The statements were scraped and parsed in Python in the original Spanish,
 thus avoiding the pitfalls of inter-translator variance, loss of nuance
 through translation, etc.
 The data was collected from September 1, 2012, the month in which formal
 peace talks were announced, through May 31, 2016, the beginning of this
 project.
 Unfortunately, this excludes the weeks leading up to the announcement of
 a final peace agreement in August 2016.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Sources
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
FARC-authored documents were scraped from the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Comunicados
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (Communiqués) section of the official FARC website 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "farc-comunicados"

\end_inset

.
 Some communiqués were authored by specific FARC generals or Secretariat
 members; however, this paper's analysis does not examine individual-level
 authorship.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Joint statements were scraped from the official Mesa de Conversaciones (Table
 for Dialogue) website of the peace negotiators 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "mesadeconversaciones"

\end_inset

.
 I exclude reports also published during the negotiations, which have a
 different purpose, format, and audience than the statements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, government statements were scraped from the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Sala de Prensa
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (Press Room) section of the president's website 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "president-2012-2015,president-2016"

\end_inset

.
 The same president, Santos, has been in office during the peace talks,
 conveniently obviating variance that might result from different administration
s.
 Because the government issues statements on all manner of topics besides
 FARC, a simple keyword search for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

FARC
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

peace
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 was used for initial screening.
 The implementation of this search differed slightly for 2012-2015 and 2016
 because of differences in the structures of the current and archived presidenti
al websites.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
All press releases from 2012-15 were scraped, and kept if 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

las Farc
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

paz
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 appeared in the text of the document.
 This was executed with a basic search script in Python during the scraping.
 A new website for the president's press releases in 2016 did not allow
 batch downloading of press releases by date; a search for the terms 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

farc
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

paz
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 using the website's search tool was performed and all results of that search
 were scraped.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Altogether, the preliminary government dataset consisted of 509 documents
 published between September 1, 2012, and May 31, 2016.
 Additional human screening of the statements was necessary to remove statements
 that contained the keywords but were (a) not relevant to the peace talks
 or (b) not reasonably attributable to the Colombian government.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For example, a statement from May 27, 2013, was titled 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Frases del Vicepresidente Joe Biden
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Quotes from Joe Biden
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

), in which the vice president expressed U.S.
 support for the peace process.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 I removed those that were irrelevant on the basis of content (e.g.
 if the peace talks with FARC were mentioned in pass or in a laundry list
 of policy issues, if a minor proportion of the document was spent discussing
 FARC, or if the statement simply noted support for the peace process from
 international organizations or third-party countries), reducing the number
 of government texts to 318.
 (Figures showing sentiment measures over time for each actor are in the
 Appendix, as are graphs showing the optimal structural breaks for each
 sentiment/actor, which were identified using the strucchange R package
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "strucchange"

\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

