\begin_layout Subsubsection
Violence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Monthly statistics on levels of ongoing violence were gathered from several
 sources.
 The number of FARC attacks per month were collected from data available
 from two Colombian conflict analysis groups.
 For 2012-2014, the source of the data was the Fundación Paz y Reconciliación
 (PARES) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "PARES-2013"

\end_inset

.
 Data from PARES was not available for 2015-2016, and was collected from
 the Centro de Recursos para el Análisis de Conflictos (CERAC) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "cerac,cerac-assessing-ceasefire"

\end_inset

.
 PARES and CERAC define attacks as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

armed actions
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

offensive actions,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 respectively.
 Statistics for the number of service personnel killed and the number of
 demobilized militants per month were collected from reports by PARES
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
PARES cites the Defense Ministry as the source for its figures.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and the Defense Ministry 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "PARES-2015,ministerio-defensa"

\end_inset

.
 It should be noted that the casualty figures include deaths from the smaller
 ongoing conflict with the ELN as well as bacrim (criminal gangs); however,
 in Defense Ministry statistics that are disaggregated by rebel group (e.g.
 number of demobilized militants), FARC's share is overwhelming.
 In the estimation, I use the log number of FARC actions because it is the
 most specific statistic.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The loessed graph rather than the log transformation is shown to give an
 idea of the general shape of the data, but obviously negative values are
 not possible.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename melt_viol.eps
	width 110text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Public opinion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Monthly public opinion data was collected from the Centro Nacional De Consultorí
a, a Colombian consultancy 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "centro-zoom,centro-imagen09-2012,centro-imagen01-2013,centro-imagen-12-2013"

\end_inset

.
 Answers to the questions, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Do you have a positive or negative image of President Juan Manuel Santos?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Do you approve of the decision of President Santos to open peace talks with
 the guerrillas?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Author's translation.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 were recorded as approval ratings for the president and for the peace process,
 respectively.
 I chose to use the log transformed peace process approval rating as the
 public opinion measure in the estimation because other domestic events
 influence the president's rating.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename melt_opinion.eps
	width 110text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Estimation method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Sentiment measures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper uses the Spanish version of the Linguistic Inquiry and Word Count
 (LIWC), which was first developed in English by Pennebaker 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "pennebaker-liwc01,pennebaker-liwc07"

\end_inset

.
 The LIWC methodology reflects Pennebaker et al.'s approach to text analysis:
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

examin[ing] people's social and psychological states by analyzing their
 use of function and emotion words,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

the former being words such articles or pronouns that are relatively devoid
 of content 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "pennebaker-chung"

\end_inset

.
 Consequently, the LIWC measures are very simple: words belonging to specific
 categories--parts of speech (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

articles,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pronouns
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) that are the aforementioned function words, or types of emotion (within
 the categories of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

positive
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

negative
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, there are subcategories such as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

optimism
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

anxiety or fear
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

)--are counted, and their share of the total words in the document is calculated
 as a percentage.
 The Spanish LIWC was translated and augmented (e.g.
 additional Spanish synonyms for words translated from the English) by Ramírez-E
sparza, Pennebaker, García, and Suriá Martínez 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ramirez-esparza-liwc"

\end_inset

.
 LIWC has been used to analyze texts written by individuals from terrorist
 organizations (and translated into English), e.g.
 transcripts of statements by Osama bin Laden and Ayman al-Zawahiri 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "pennebaker-chung"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I use LIWC measures for positive emotion and negative emotion and applied
 loess for smoothing.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Although I initially planned to also use third-person plural pronouns, which
 have been found to be used at higher rates by extremist groups 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "pennebaker-chung"

\end_inset

, as it turns out the government uses them more frequently than FARC on
 average, and they are highly correlated with both positive and negative
 emotion.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

These statistics are admittedly crude word counts; the categories of words
 are not tailored for political science purposes or for the conflict of
 interest; and the dictionaries are intended for the analysis of personality
 traits of individual authors, not organizations.
 Nevertheless, the LIWC sentiment measures can reveal insights into the
 nature of the documents, and testing LIWC's applicability to these kinds
 of texts is also valuable.
 Methods such as Principal Component Analysis (PCA) and traditional time-series
 analysis proved to be unsuitable, owing to the high variance in the length
 of documents and the highly irregular issuance of statements, respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Modelling hidden states
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first estimation task is to use the shares of positive and negative
 sentiment in a sequence of texts to model a Markov regime-switching model,
 in which the hidden regimes are discrete states that represent the government
 or FARC's willingness to negotiate--that is, whether they are in a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hardline
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 versus 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

conciliatory
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 state.
 In other words, we are interested in the random variable that represents
 FARC's (or the government's) willingness to negotiate, which is directly
 unobservable.
 Instead, we observe the stream of positive and negative sentiment of the
 FARC documents, which emanate from the latent state that FARC is in at
 the time.
 (For the purposes of simplifying this discussion, I assume a state space
 with two possible states, but the model can theoretically be generalized
 to any number of states.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This hidden Markov model (HMM) is a special case of a first-order Markov
 process.
 The sequence of states is a Markov chain: the probabilities of being in
 a hardline or conciliatory state, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{H}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{C}$
\end_inset

, respectively, exhibit the Markov property, namely that the probability
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{H}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{C}$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 depends only on the realization of the state 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{H}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{C}$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t-1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the realization of state at 
\begin_inset Formula $t-1$
\end_inset

 captures all information about what occurred prior to 
\begin_inset Formula $t-1$
\end_inset

.
 I assume that the process is stationary, i.e.
 the probability of moving from state 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 to state 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 does not depend on how long the process has been in state 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At each time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 the process is in a hidden state and we observe the emissions, or symbols,
 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{t}$
\end_inset

 from time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 The probability of an observed emission 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 depends only on the state 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "jurafsky"

\end_inset

 Thus, we can compute the probability of a stream of observations 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{1},...O_{T}$
\end_inset

 by using a shortcut called the forward-backward algorithmn to sum over
 all of the hidden state sequences that could have generated that the stream
 of observations.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rabiner1989tutorial"

\end_inset

 In this case, the observed sequence of emissions is a stream of loessed
 sentiment measures: the percent of negative emotion words in FARC statements
 might look like 
\begin_inset Formula $(0.01,0.12,0.04,0.01)$
\end_inset

.
 We are interested in the corresponding sequence of hidden states which
 generated the sequence of emissions: for example 
\begin_inset Formula $(S_{H},S_{H},S_{C},S_{H}).$
\end_inset

 We are also interested in the transition probabilities, which represent
 probability of moving from 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{t}=S_{i}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{t+1}=S_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 These probabilities are represented in transition matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
[
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{blockarray}{ccc}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

 & S_{H} & S_{C} 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{block}{c(cc)}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

   S_{H} & P_{HH} & P_{HC} 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

   S_{C} & P_{CH} & P_{CC} 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{block}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{blockarray}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

 
\backslash
]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each entry 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{ij}=Pr(S_{t+1}=state_{j}|S_{t}=state_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{HH}$
\end_inset

 is the probability of transitioning from a hardline state to a hardline
 state, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{HC}$
\end_inset

 is the probability of moving from a hardline to a concessions state, and
 so on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This discussion has used a discrete state space with two possible states;
 however, it can be generalized to a larger number of states.
 In some cases substantive/theoretical grounds may define an appropriate
 number of latent states for a HMM; however, because the spectrum from 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hardline
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

conciliatory
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 can reasonably be split into different numbers of states, I adopt an agnostic
 approach.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Optimizing the number of states
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The best-fitting number of states for a HMM can be identified by the Bayesian
 information criterion (BIC) and the Akaike information criterion (AIC)
 values.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In other applications of hidden Markov models, the number of states is not
 mathematically optimized because it and the labels attached to the states
 tend to determined by substantive criteria: e.g.
 in medical examples, values for various indicators of health that fall
 within certain ranges correspond to pre-set states, and in economic examples,
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bull
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bear
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 markets are modelled with two states that clearly correspond with economic
 indicators.
 This paper uses a more agnostic approach.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 To keep interpretation across the FARC and government models comparable,
 I specify the same number of latent states.
 The substantive interpretation of the model accommodates small numbers
 of latent states: for instance, two latent states would correspond to a
 dichotomy between 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hardline
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

conciliatory,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 while three latent states might represent low, moderate, and high levels
 of willingness to negotiate, representing hardline, moderate and conciliatory
 regimes, respectively.
 As the number of states increases, the substantive interpretation of transition
 probabilities across these states becomes more challenging, and a higher
 number of states means that fitting the model becomes difficult because
 transitions between any two given states may be rare or nonexistent.
 I weigh these considerations against the models' log-likelihood, BIC, and
 AIC values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Labelling the states
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because HMM estimation does not attach substantive labels to the states,
 such labelling must be done post-estimation.
 I explore two possible methods.
 First, I construct a ranking of the unlabelled states in order of relative
 willingness to negotiate using measures of central tendency.
 For example, the state with the highest mean positive emotion and lowest
 mean negative emotion would correspond to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 willingness (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

conciliatory
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

), while the state with the lowest mean positive emotion and the highest
 mean negative emotion should be the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

low
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 willingness (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hardline
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 I also use a multi-choice decision matrix to optimize the ranking of states
 based on the average sentiment measured in each unlabelled state.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Modelling sentiment response
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second part of this paper uses a Markov process to model the response
 of sentiment to sentiment.
 The irregularity of the data does present some challenges, as there are
 stretches in the time-ordered sequence of FARC and government texts where
 little alternation occurs.
 (For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $F,F,F,G,G,G,G,F$
\end_inset

.) This is partly owing to the fact that the dataset includes roughly three
 times as many statements from the government as from FARC and that both
 actors sometimes release multiple statements on the same day.
 I assume that the sequence of time-ordered statements represents a single
 Markov process, like a back-and-forth debate in which each text responds
 to the document that immediately preceded it.
 This means that a FARC document could respond to a previous FARC document.
 Repetitive issuances, such as a series of low-sentiment documents, might
 indicate a strategy where actors make public denunciations to get better
 terms at the negotiating table, or they might be directed at another audience.
 For example, the government might issue several low-sentiment statements
 to show the political opposition or the public that it is being tough on
 FARC.
 Our main interest, however, is whether an actor's sentiment can predict
 the sentiment of other actor's next statement: for instance, if, following
 a FARC statement with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 sentiment, it is more likely that the following government statement is
 also 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 sentiment rather than 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

low.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To categorize overall sentiment of these texts as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

low,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 I created a new measure defined by LIWC-based research that found that
 in normal usage, positive emotion words occur twice as frequently as negative
 emotion words 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "pennebaker-chung"

\end_inset

.
 I constructed an indicator for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

low
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 sentiment, taking on the former value if the loessed proportion of positive
 words in a statement is at least twice the loessed proportion of negative
 words, and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

low
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 otherwise.
 I constructed another categorical variable representing the four possible
 states: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

FARC/low,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

FARC/high,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

government/low,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

government/high.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As before, the probabilities of transitioning from state to state are represente
d in a Markov transition matrix.
 I estimate the probabilities using a multinomial logit with maximum likelihood
 estimation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "croissant-mlogit"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
[
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{blockarray}{ccccc}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

 & F_{L} & F_{H} & G_{L} & G{H} 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{block}{c(cccc)}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

   F_{L} & P_{F_{L}, F_{L}} & P_{F_{L}, F_{H}} & P_{F_{L}, G_{L}} & P_{F_{L},
 G_{H}} 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

   F_{H} & P_{F_{H}, F_{L}} & P_{F_{H}, F_{H}} & P_{F_{H}, G_{L}} & P_{F_{H},
 G_{H}} 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

   G_{L} & P_{G_{L}, F_{L}} & P_{G_{L}, F_{H}} & P_{G_{L}, G_{L}} & P_{G_{L},
 G_{H}} 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

   G_{H} & P_{G_{H}, F_{L}} & P_{G_{H}, F_{H}} & P_{G_{H}, G_{L}} & P_{G_{H},
 G_{H}} 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{block}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{blockarray}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

 
\backslash
]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Like before, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i,j}=Pr(S_{t+1}=state_{j}|S_{t}=state_{i}).$
\end_inset

 We are most interested the diagonal, which reflects the probability of
 that each state is persistent, and the entries 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{F_{H},G_{H}},P_{F_{L},G_{L}},P_{G_{H},F_{H}},P_{G_{L},F_{L}}$
\end_inset

, which represent the probabilities that an actor will respond with the
 same level of sentiment that the other actor used in the previous statement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Results and discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Hidden Markov model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Optimal number of latent states
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A hidden Markov model was fitted for each actor using the depmixS4 R package
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "depmixs4"

\end_inset

.
 (For a note on how this package's implementation of the expectation-maximizatio
n algorithm with randomly generated start values affected the results, see
 the Appendix.) First, however, I optimized the number of latent states.
 The table below shows the BIC and AIC values for HMMs fitted separately
 for FARC and the government with 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1:5$
\end_inset

 latent states.
 I tested additional models that include covariates for the level of violence
 (log number of FARC actions recorded for the month) and public opinion
 (log monthly approval rating for Santos's decision to hold peace talks
 with guerrillas).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


