\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Comparing Model (1) vs.
 (2) and Model (3) vs.
 (4) shows that the inclusion of violence and public opinion covariates
 does little to improve fit.
 Going from 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2,$
\end_inset

 the improvement in BIC and AIC values demonstrates that a mixture is a
 better fit for the data than a single state.
 However, for the FARC models with and without covariates, the BIC values
 suggest that 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

 optimizes the number of latent states; although 
\begin_inset Formula $n=4$
\end_inset

 has a slightly better BIC value than 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

 in both models, the improvement is marginal and is weighed against the
 consideration that the fewest possible number of latent states should be
 used.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The AIC values for the FARC models, however, as well as both the BIC and
 AIC values for the government models, favor a specification with 
\begin_inset Formula $n=5$
\end_inset

.
 However, these improvements in fit must be balanced against the tradeoff
 in the interpretability of results in a model with so many states (e.g.
 what is the substantive meaning of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

transition from 1/5 to 2/5 hardline
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

?) and the difficulty of substantively labelling a large number of states.
 Consequently, the following analysis will proceed with a HMM with 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

 latent states, and without public opinion and violence covariates.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Labelling the states
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The latent states represent high, moderate, and low willingness to negotiate.
 However, the HMM estimation does not attach substantive labels to numbered
 states, nor does it order the states by magnitude.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It is readily apparent that with 
\begin_inset Formula $n>2$
\end_inset

 states, labelling becomes increasingly complex.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For instance, state 1 may correspond with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 state 2 with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

low,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and state 3 with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

moderate.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I first use the mean and median sentiment measures for each unlabelled state
 to devise a ranking that would correspond with the labels 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

medium,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

low.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 For instance, the state with the lowest negative and highest positive sentiment
 should be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 willingness to negotiate, i.e.
 the conciliatory regime, while the state with the highest negative and
 lowest positive sentiment would be hardline/
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

low
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 willingness.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

