\begin_layout Standard
Across the board, the standard deviations relative to the means are high,
 due to the spread of the data and the fact that some states rarely occur.
 The mean and median agree on their predictions, and positive sentiment
 for FARC and negative sentiment for the government do produce the same
 rankings, but the rankings based on negative sentiment contradict each
 other.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because of these contradictions, I use a multi-choice decision matrix, implement
ed in the MCDM R package, to identify the optimal ranking based on different
 methods for computing multi-criteria decisions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "martin-mcdm"

\end_inset

.
 The ranking maximizes negative sentiment and minimizes positive sentiment:
 the state ranked first is low willingness and the state ranked third is
 high willingness.
 When using either the mean or median sentiment, the overall decision matrix
 maps states 
\begin_inset Formula $1,2,3$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

moderate,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

low
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (hardline), and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (conciliatory).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
HMM results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Markov transition matrices shown below represent the probabilities of
 regime switching for FARC and the government, estimated using the loessed
 negative and positive emotion measures and labeled according to the results
 of the decision matrix.
 First, looking at the diagonals, we find that when FARC is hardline (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

low
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 willingness) or moderate, there is a high probability that it will continue
 to be hardline or moderate.
 For the government, on the other hand, the transition probabilities in
 each row are more evenly dispersed.
 These probabilities may shed light on the lasting impact of shocks such
 as violent attacks during negotiations; it appears that if a shock should
 put FARC in a hardline state, it may be hard to transition out of that
 state again, but the same is not true of the government.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Other interesting results are that FARC is predicted to never transition
 directly from low to high and vice versa, and to never transition from
 moderate to low: yet all of these transitions do occur, perhaps because
 of rounding, in the graphs below, which show the estimated states of FARC
 and the government over the time period of the negotiations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The government is most likely to transition to a state of moderate willingness
 from any state.
 However, when the government is in the state of moderate willingness, it
 is roughly equally likely to transition to a hardline or conciliatory state
 (
\begin_inset Formula $0.24$
\end_inset

 versus 
\begin_inset Formula $0.28$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


