\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename hmm_farc.eps
	width 100text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename hmm_govt.eps
	width 100text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both FARC and the government spend little time in the moderate state, which
 suggests that a model with two latent states might actually have been preferabl
e for ease of interpretation.
 Overall, the government's willingness to negotiate is more volatile, with
 frequent regime switching from low to high throughout the time interval.
 The irregularity and frequency of data explains some of this volatility:
 statements may be issued days or months apart, and there are three times
 as many government documents.
 But although the higher frequency of government statements affects the
 appearance of the regime-switching graph, the government does have lower
 probabilities of state persistence, as seen in the diagonal of the transition
 matrix.
 The higher probabilities in FARC's transition matrix diagonal are consistent
 with the group's less volatile regime-switching.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A potential explanation of the government's volatile transitions is that
 its statements must address many different audiences and groups: toward
 FARC, the government must be a tough negotiator; for domestic critics,
 the government must appease hawks' objections about specific provisions
 such as seats in the legislature for ex-guerrillas or amnesty from prosecution;
 for the military, the government must reassure them about concerns regarding
 potential prosecution of military personnel for acts committed during the
 war; for the international community, the government pledges its commitment
 to peace as it possibly seeks regional or United Nations assistance with
 the implementation of any deal; and for the public, the government must
 work against their skepticism, assure survivors that the voices of victims
 of the conflict have been heard, and convince people to vote yes in a referendu
m.
 FARC, on the other hand, addresses its 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

constituency,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 rank and file fighters who need to be persuaded to demobilize; the government
 and occasionally the right wing (e.g.
 accusing Uribe of being a paramilitary); and sometimes the nation.
 There is less at stake for FARC should it fail to appease one of these
 audiences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Anecdotally, we may consider some events that are objectively likely to
 be associated with the government's willingness to negotiate.
 In June 2015, FARC launched a series of attacks, bombing infrastructure
 such as oil pipelines in Norte de Santander, Putumayo, and Nariño, resulting
 in an oil spill that caused severe environmental damage and contaminated
 the water supply of thousands; and bombing power stations that supplied
 electricity to the cities of Buenaventura and Tumaco 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "guardian-pipeline,colombiareports-attacks,colombiapeace-timelines,telesur-timeline"

\end_inset

.
 This time period coincides with an episode of frequent regime-switching
 observed in the government graph, but it coincides with a period of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 willingness to negotiate in the FARC model.
 Although bombings and conciliatory sentiment seem contradictory, the conciliato
ry sentiments in FARC's statements during this period may explain how the
 peace talks continued despite the attacks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The government's state of low willingness to negotiate in November 2014
 following FARC's kidnapping of a general seems consistent; the government
 suspended peace talks from November 16, and resumed them on December 9
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Although threatening to suspend or suspending talks (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

walking away from the table
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) may seem like a common bluffing maneuver, the government carried out this
 threat very rarely during these negotiations: in fact, only on these two
 occasions.
 FARC suspended talks on one occasion in 2013, over objections about the
 government's plan to hold a referendum 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "colombiapeace-timelines"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 after the general was returned 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "colombiapeace-timelines,telesur-timeline"

\end_inset

.
 This episode, too, falls within FARC's long spell of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 willingness to negotiate, and again, the conciliatory sentiment of FARC
 (combined with the safe return of the general) may help explain why the
 peace talks recovered from this crisis.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Validation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With noisy and irregular data, matching events to states is imperfect.
 To evaluate the validity of the hidden Markov model, I use a regression
 of joint statement sentiment on the predicted states of willingness on
 the day that the statement was issued, with linear interaction terms, to
 test the first hypothesis that willingness to negotiate is positively associate
d with positive sentiment of joint statements and negatively associated
 with negative sentiment.
 I also use a logistic regression to test the second hypothesis that there
 is a positive association between conciliatory states and the issuance
 of joint statements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{table}[!htbp] 
\backslash
centering 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

  
\backslash
caption{Does Willingness to Negotiate Predict Joint Sentiment?} 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

  
\backslash
label{} 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{tabular}{@{
\backslash
extracolsep{5pt}}lcc} 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash
[-1.8ex]
\backslash
hline 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hline 
\backslash

\backslash
[-1.8ex] 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash
[-1.8ex] & Negative & Positive 
\backslash

\backslash
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash
[-1.8ex] & (1) & (2) 
\backslash

\backslash
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hline 
\backslash

\backslash
[-1.8ex] 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

FARC low willingness & 0.39 & 5.47 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

 & (3.51) & (21.49) 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

FARC high willingness & 1.23 & 15.53 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

 & (3.71) & (22.69) 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Government low willingness & 10.30** & 72.37** 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

 & (4.79) & (29.29) 
