\begin_layout Standard
Regarding hypothesis (1), the interaction terms show that when both FARC
 and the government are in the low willingness (hardline) state, this is
 associated with much lower levels of positive sentiment and slightly lower
 levels of negative sentiment, relative to the moderate willingness state.
 An even more pronounced effect is observed when FARC is in a conciliatory
 state but the government is in a hardline state, relative to the moderate
 willingness state.
 These results provide some support for the HMM estimations, although their
 statistical power is hampered by the small number of joint sentiment observatio
ns.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are also interested in whether willingness to negotiate is correlated
 with whether a joint statement is issued at all.
 Since joint statements can announce agreements on policy, progress reports,
 or the next steps in the negotiating schedule, their occurrence may be
 a metric for how much is being accomplished in the negotiations.
 To test whether the states estimated by the HMM can predict joint statement
 issuance, I created date/state indicator variables for FARC and the government
 for each day in the negotiations period, and a dummy variable for joint
 statement issuance.
 I use a logistic regression with linear interaction terms.
 However, none of the results are statistically significant, and the hypothesis
 does not find support.
 (Table in Appendix.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Sentiment response results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I estimate the responsiveness of sentiment to sentiment, in the form of
 a Markov transition matrix.
 The probabilities in this matrix are calculated using a multinomial logit
 with maximum likelihood estimation.
 I test four models: The first is a simple MNL of 
\begin_inset Formula $State_{t+1}$
\end_inset

 as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $State_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 Model (2) adds year indicators to control for year effects, because of
 potential associations between sentiment and time (e.g.
 one might argue that sentiment in later years should be higher because
 of the survival of the peace negotiations).
 Model (3) adds covariates for violence and public opinion to the base model,
 in the form of log transformed number of FARC actions recorded in that
 month and log transformed presidential approval ratings for that month.
 Model (4) includes both the year indicators and the violence and public
 opinion covariates.
 Thus, Model (1) is nested in each of the other models, and Models (2) and
 (3) are nested in Model (4), the full model.
 
\end_layout

