\begin_layout Standard
Is sentiment is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sticky
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

? Low government sentiment has a high probability 
\begin_inset Formula $(0.62)$
\end_inset

 of continuing in subsequent time periods, although it should be noted that
 this was also the most common state occurring in the data.
 High government sentiment is less likely to persist 
\begin_inset Formula $(0.30)$
\end_inset

 and is more likely to be followed by low government sentiment 
\begin_inset Formula $(0.52)$
\end_inset

, on the other hand.
 Persistence of FARC's sentiment is less frequent, with 
\begin_inset Formula $0.10$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0.33$
\end_inset

 for low and high sentiment.
 Overall, these results suggest that dire pronouncements from either negotiant
 do not necessarily spell doom for a peace process.
 These results put us on our way to answering questions such as whether
 a shock such as a terrorist attack permanently derail sentiment, which
 may help us make inferences about the effect of attacks on the peace process.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Do actors respond to sentiment with the same level of sentiment? Both FARC
 and the government are more likely to respond to high sentiment with high,
 and low sentiment with low, although consecutive statements are often from
 the same actor.
 There is a 
\begin_inset Formula $0.01$
\end_inset

 probability that the response to a low-sentiment government statement will
 be a low-sentiment statement from FARC, versus a 
\begin_inset Formula $0.17$
\end_inset

 probability that the response will be a high-sentiment FARC statement.
 There is a 
\begin_inset Formula $0.16$
\end_inset

 probability that the response to a high-sentiment government statement
 is a high-sentiment FARC statement, compared with a 
\begin_inset Formula $0.02$
\end_inset

 probability that it will be a low-sentiment FARC statement.
 The government, on the other hand, is twice as likely 
\begin_inset Formula $(0.26$
\end_inset

 versus 
\begin_inset Formula $0.13)$
\end_inset

 to respond with high positive sentiment following a low-sentiment FARC
 statement, and more likely (
\begin_inset Formula $0.40$
\end_inset

 versus 
\begin_inset Formula $0.24)$
\end_inset

 to respond to a high positive FARC statement with a low sentiment statement
 of its own rather than a high sentiment statement.(The statement most likely
 to follow a government statement of any kind is another government statement.)
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The graph below shows the predicted probability of each state.
 Relative to the beginning of the peace process, high government sentiment
 is much more likely and low FARC sentiment much less likely, although high
 FARC sentiment remains fairly flat throughout.
 This may reflect 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

trust
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 built over the course of the negotiations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename mnl_pr.eps
	width 110text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Summary of findings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper is a first attempt at applying text and sentiment analysis methods
 to the study of conflict negotiation.
 So far research on negotiations processes has often focused on the effect
 of violence, while research that does look at texts tends to focus on peace
 agreements.
 This paper models the process that produces those agreements.
 Measuring the ongoing state of a negotiation process can contribute to
 research on the peace process spoilers and on the relationships between
 negotiations, agreement provisions, and peace survival.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the results in this paper suggest, using sentiment analysis to measure
 actors' willingness to negotiate is a promising frontier.
 My choice of a three-state hidden Markov model was guided by considerations
 of model fit as well as interpretability, but the results actually suggest
 that a dichotomy of hardline/conciliatory may be preferable.
 Surprising, too, were the findings that a sentiment-only model was as good
 of a fit as a model that included covariates for levels of public opinion
 and violence.
 Future HMM estimation could thus be considerably simpler than it was in
 this paper.
 With that said, substantive labelling of latent states is essentially a
 classification problem that could be resolved using machine learning techniques.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The transition probabilities of the HMMs indicate a high level of state
 persistence for FARC and a more even distribution of probabilities for
 the government.
 Although this may at first seem counterintuitive, I suggest some theoretical
 reasons that the government's regime-switching is more frequent and volatile
 than FARC's, namely that the government's statements must address numerous
 political and public audiences.
 Although it does not offer a causal explanation, the regime-switching model
 also suggests a potential theory for how the peace process may have survived
 two crises--FARC's kidnapping of a general and FARC's bombing campaign
 of infrastructure--because of positive sentiment in FARC's statements during
 these periods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In validating the HMM results, I found that higher FARC/government willingness
 to negotiate is not necessarily correlated with more positive sentiment
 in joint statements, and that the two actors appear to have differential
 effects on joint sentiment.
 I was unable to find support for the hypothesis that joint statement sentiment
 is correlated with FARC and government willingness to negotiate.
 The relationship between individual negotiants' output and documents from
 negotiations, final or otherwise, deserves further scrutiny.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sentiment response model supports the hypothesis that one actor's sentiment
 can predict the other actor's sentiment in a subsequent statement and that
 actors mirror each other's sentiment.
 Surprisingly, FARC was generally more likely to respond positively and
 the government was generally more likely to respond negatively, and government
 negativity was more likely to persist.
 These trends of persistence and volatility, as well as the reasoning behind
 repetitive issuances of statements, might be illuminated by a game theoretical
 model of bargaining that incorporates these statements as signals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Other research building on this paper might consider measuring sentiment
 in ways other than LIWC.
 Using a general dictionary, and using very general categories such as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

positive
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

negative
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 have the advantages of being extendable to other conflicts or to non-conflict
 applications.
 However, a dictionary with political science-specific terms, or even conflict-s
pecific terms (e.g.
 terms that might refer to a specific leaders, locations, events, etc.) may
 be the way forward for more refined analysis and more specific results.
 Building custom dictionaries requires extensive background knowledge and
 time; however, as dictionaries such as LIWC are not available in all languages,
 custom dictionaries may be necessary for comparative research.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relationship between sentiment and the level of violence is of obvious
 importance.
 With disaggregated violence statistics, further research may be able to
 unearth the relationships between specific kinds of violence (e.g.
 bombings, murders, etc.) and trends in sentiment, and reveal insights about
 peace process spoilers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Particular to this case study, the data can be updated to include statements
 leading up to the August 2016 peace agreement announcement or the referendum.
 Given that provisions of a peace agreement can predict whether peace will
 survive, much can be learned from studying the process that produces these
 agreements.
 Examining the relationship between the sentiment of texts from the peace
 process and the final agreement may enable us to predict peace survival
 from negotiations sentiment.
 Another interesting area of future inquiry is the Colombian government's
 imminent negotiations with the ELN, which could be a step toward extending
 these results to other conflicts and contexts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
