\begin_layout Subsubsection
Estimation: A note on fitting hidden Markov models using depmixS4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expectation-maximization algorithm used in fitting hidden Markov models
 to data, implemented in the depmixS4 R package, randomly generates start
 values by generating random uniform values for the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{t}(j)=P(S_{t}=j|O_{1:T},z_{1:T},\theta')$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{1:T}$
\end_inset

 are the observations, 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{1:T}$
\end_inset

 are covariates, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta'$
\end_inset

 is the set of initial model parameters.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "depmixs4"

\end_inset

 Even when the seed is set to a fixed value, the EM algorithm does not always
 produce the same results because it randomly assigns the initial state,
 meaning that it does not generate the same transition matrix every single
 time.
 It does, however, reliably generate a limited number of transition matrices:
 three different matrices for FARC, and four for the government.
 (The rows of these matrices may be arranged in different orders, but they
 are equivalent because substantive labelling of the states i.e.
 rows occurs subsequently.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

same
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 matrices usually had identical values, but in a few cases differed by 0.001,
 or rarely by 0.01, because of rounding during fitting.) I fitted the model
 1,000 times for FARC and the government separately, and used the most frequentl
y occurring models (the selected FARC model occurred 596/1000 times, while
 the government model occurred 916/1000).
\end_layout

